message.content:
The grammar’s non-terminals are extremely inter-connected: almost every non-terminal can expand into a pair of other non-terminals and many of them can also deliver a terminal directly.  
For each of the 36 terminals that occur in the target string we can find at least one non-terminal with a direct production to that terminal (for example, t9 via NT37 or NT31; t34 via NT4 or NT25; … ; t85 via NT34 or NT39).  

Because:

• S expands to two large sub-phrases (S → NT12 NT8 or S → NT21 NT39).  
• Each of NT12, NT8, NT21 and NT39 is mutually recursive with numerous other symbols (e.g. NT12 → NT26 NT11, NT11 → NT23 NT5, NT5 → NT38 NT41, …) that allow indefinite concatenation of further non-terminals.  
• Those recursion chains eventually bottom out in the direct terminal rules just mentioned.

it is always possible to construct a derivation that produces any required sequence of terminals, including the given 36-token sequence (one can, for instance, let the left child of S generate the first k tokens and the right child generate the remainder; thanks to the unbounded recursive concatenations inside NT12/NT8 or NT21/NT39, k can be chosen arbitrarily).

Hence the string can be generated by the grammar.

Yes
